Durban - A policeman was arrested during a shootout in New Germany, west of Durban, on Friday. He was allegedly in a car with two other men who tried to kidnap a woman on Friday afternoon. Captain Nqobile Gwala, police spokesperson, said the 28-year-old woman was walking along Dinkelman Road, New Germany, when a silver Hyundai with three occupants stopped next to her. "At gunpoint, the suspects forced the victim into the vehicle. They robbed the woman of her cell phone and she managed to open the door and get out of the vehicle. The suspects then drove off. A police officer from the eThekwini Inner and Outer West Cluster Task Team witnessed the incident and pursued the suspects to the Clermont area. The suspects fired shots at the police officer returned fire. A suspect was fatally wounded. With the help of the K9 Unit another suspect, who is a police officer stationed at KwaMashu was arrested while the third suspect managed to flee the scene,” Gwala said. Gwala said a 27-year-old man appeared at the Pinetown Magistrate’s Court and Monday on charges of robbery and attempted murder. “This incident once again proves that police are strategically placed to tackle criminal activity in our society. This arrest will serve as warning to other criminals who are hiding behind our SAPS badge. The vast majority of our police officers are principled and will not hesitate to arrest any person who commits crime. Nobody is untouchable,” Major General Bheki Langa, KwaZulu-Natal Acting Provincial Commissioner, said. Daily News